## POST 342 â€” ðŸŽ“ RECAP: MOVING AVERAGES

**Source:** `https://education.signalpilot.io/curriculum/beginner/08-moving-averages.html`

---

### ð• Twitter

**Copy:**
> Moving averages: the simplest trend filter.
>
> Price above MA = bullish bias
> Price below MA = bearish bias
>
> Not magic, just math. A smoothed view of direction.
>
> ðŸŽ“ [link]

**Image:** Chart showing price above/below moving average with trend direction

**Hashtags:** #MovingAverages #TradingBasics #SignalPilot #TradingEducation

---

### ðŸ“¸ Instagram

**Caption:**
> ðŸ“ˆ BACK TO BASICS: MOVING AVERAGES
>
> Simple but powerful trend filters.
>
> ðŸ“Š WHAT THEY DO:
>
> â†’ Smooth price data
> â†’ Show average price over X periods
> â†’ Filter trend direction
>
> ðŸ“ COMMON TYPES:
>
> âœ¦ SMA (Simple Moving Average)
> â†’ Equal weight to all periods
> â†’ Slower, smoother
>
> âœ¦ EMA (Exponential Moving Average)
> â†’ More weight to recent prices
> â†’ Faster, more responsive
>
> ðŸŽ¯ HOW TO USE:
>
> â†’ Price ABOVE MA = bullish bias
> â†’ Price BELOW MA = bearish bias
> â†’ MA slope = trend strength
>
> ðŸ“ COMMON PERIODS:
>
> â†’ 20 MA = short-term
> â†’ 50 MA = medium-term
> â†’ 200 MA = long-term
>
> Moving averages LAG. They confirm, not predict.
>
> Free lesson ðŸŽ“ Link in bio
>
> âš ï¸ Educational only. Not financial advice.

