---

### ð• Twitter

**Copy:**
> Inverse FVG: when price fills a gap and that zone becomes support/resistance.
>
> The inefficiency gets "inverted" into a reaction zone.
>
> Gaps don't just fillâ€”they flip.
>
> Understanding inversion adds depth to FVG analysis.
>
> Learn the concept â†’ [link]

**Image:** Chart showing FVG that got filled, then acted as support/resistance

**Hashtags:** #InverseFVG #FairValueGap #SmartMoney #SignalPilot #TradingEducation

---

### ðŸ“¸ Instagram

**Caption:**
> ðŸ”„ INVERSE FAIR VALUE GAPS
>
> Filled gaps don't disappearâ€”they transform.
>
> THE CONCEPT:
> â†’ FVG forms (inefficiency)
> â†’ Price returns and fills it
> â†’ The filled zone now acts as S/R
> â†’ Gap "inverts" its role
>
> WHY IT WORKS:
> â†’ Orders were filled in that zone
> â†’ Creates memory in the market
> â†’ Previous inefficiency = current efficiency
> â†’ Zone now has two-sided interest
>
> HOW TO USE:
> â†’ Mark FVGs as they form
> â†’ Note when they get filled
> â†’ Watch for price to return again
> â†’ Expect potential reaction at inverse zone
>
> Gaps evolve. Track their lifecycle.
>
> ðŸŽ“ Full lesson in curriculum
>
> ðŸ”— Link in bio

